<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg016' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 16</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >For the People of <placeName  key='Megalopolis'>Megalopolis</placeName></title>; see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). <placeName  key='Megalopolis'>Megalopolis</placeName> was a relatively new city in the area called <placeName  key='Arcadia'>Arcadia</placeName>, in the <placeName  key='Peloponnese'>Peloponnese</placeName>. It had been founded in <date  when='-0371'>371 BCE</date> after <placeName  key='Thebes'>Thebes</placeName> defeated <placeName  key='Sparta'>Sparta</placeName> at the battle of <placeName  key='Leuctra'>Leuctra</placeName>. The Thebans intended for <placeName  key='Megalopolis'>Megalopolis</placeName> to serve as a capital city of <placeName  key='Arcadia'>Arcadia</placeName>, and to unite the region. They hoped that a united <placeName  key='Arcadia'>Arcadia</placeName> would limit <placeName  key='Sparta'>Sparta</placeName>’s power in the <placeName  key='Peloponnese'>Peloponnese</placeName>. But in <date  when='-0353'>353 BCE</date>, <placeName  key='Thebes'>Thebes</placeName> was occupied by a war against <placeName  key='Phocis'>Phocis</placeName>, in central <placeName  key='Greece'>Greece</placeName>, and <placeName  key='Sparta'>Sparta</placeName> was free to assert control, once again, over the <placeName  key='Peloponnese'>Peloponnese</placeName>. The people of <placeName  key='Megalopolis'>Megalopolis</placeName> asked for <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to become their ally. In this speech, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> argues before the Athenian <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> in favor of an alliance with <placeName  key='Megalopolis'>Megalopolis</placeName>. The Athenians did not take his advice, but followed a policy of neutrality advocated by <name  type='person'>Eubulus</name>. (Source for dates: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 437</bibl>). </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
